.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Thorpe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Lancashire): from Middle English <i>thorp(e)</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>thorp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from any of several places called Thorp(e), which are most frequent in Yorkshire, the Midlands, and East Anglia. Compare   Throop  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Trupp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Hermann, Reinhold.","English (Herefordshire and Monmouthshire): variant of   Thorpe  , or from a place so named, such as Thrupp (Berkshire, Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire), Thrupe (Somerset), Throop (Dorset, Hampshire, Somerset), and Throope (Wiltshire).","Altered form of German   Trapp  ."]},{"name":"Throop","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>throp</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>throp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from Throop in Hampshire, Throope in Wiltshire, Thrup in Oxfordshire, or any of the places called Thrupp in Berkshire, Gloucestershire, and Northamptonshire. Compare   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharpe","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Thorpe  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Thorp","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Thorpe  .","Scandinavian: variant of   Torp  ."]},{"name":"Troup","meanings":["Scottish (eastern): habitational name from a place in the parish of Gamrie, near Banff. The placename is unexplained, perhaps a Pictish cognate of Welsh <i>trwp</i> ‘vessel, dish, basin’.","Possibly also English, a metathesized form of   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharp","meanings":["English: variant of   Thorpe  ."]}]},{"name":"Stephen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English spelling of the name of the first Christian martyr (Acts 6–7), whose feast is accordingly celebrated next after Christ's own (  26 December ). His name is derived from the Greek word <i>stephanos</i> ‘garland, crown’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stephan","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , preserving the vowels of the Greek name."]},{"name":"Steven","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , reflecting the normal pronunciation of the name in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Stephen de Thorpe II de Merflet was born about 1198, in Marfleet, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Stephen de Thorpe I, was 22 and his mother, Maud, was 19. He married Matilda about 1229. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died after 1249, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1198–Aft. 1249":"umbes 1198–pärast 1249","1198–1249":"1198–1249","1202–Female":"1202–Surnud","1230–1296":"1230–1296","1232–Male":"1232–Surnud","1178–1199":"1178–1199","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","Aft. 1249":"pärast 1249","1198":"1198","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","ABT 1229":"umbes 1229","1180":"1180","1249":"1249","1202":"1202","1178":"1178","1199":"1199","1232":"1232","about 1198":"umbes 1198","about 1199":"umbes 1199","about 1232":"umbes 1232","Holderness, of Marfleet, Yorkshire, England":"Marfleet, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Marfleet, Yorkshire, England":"Marfleet, Yorkshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Marfleet, Holderness, Yorkshire":"Marfleet, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1198–Aft. 1249":"noin 1198–1249 jälkeen","1198–1249":"1198–1249","1202–Female":"1202–Kuollut","1230–1296"